The U.S. Campaign Against Chinese Technology
New York — — Among the worst foreign policy decisions made by the previous generation (even including earlier generations) of Americans was the 2003 invasion of Iraq, dubbed the "war of choice," which claimed the goal of eliminating —— in reality, nonexistent —— weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity to understand the erroneous logic behind this disastrous decision has become unprecedentedly significant, as the same logic is now being invoked to defend similarly misleading U.S. policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the erroneous logic of Richard Cheney, the then-U.S. Vice President, who claimed that we should take action as if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists (for example, 1%) was certain.
But this line of reasoning almost always leads to erroneous decisions.
However, the U.S. and some of its allies are now using Cheneism to attack China's technology.
According to the U.S. government, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should treat it as inevitably harmful and ban it.
Correct decisions would apply probability estimates to various alternatives.
A generation ago, policymakers in the U.S. should not have considered the alleged 1% risk of mass destructive weapons falling into the hands of terrorists alone, but also the 99% risk of initiating a war based on multiple flawed assumptions.
By highlighting only that 1% risk, Cheney (as well as many others) diverted public attention, causing people to overlook the fact that the Iraq War was actually unjustified and would severely destabilize the political situation in the Middle East and globally.
But the problem with Cheneism is not just that it acts on minimal risks without considering the extremely high potential costs, but that politicians always stoke fear for some hidden agenda.
This is what U.S. leaders are doing again: by pointing out and exaggerating certain minor risks, they are instilling fear among Chinese tech companies.
One of the most relevant (though not the only) cases is the U.S. government's attack on telecommunications technology company Huawei.
The U.S. is gradually closing off its domestic market to the company and striving to stifle its global business.
Like Iraq, the U.S. may ultimately cause a senseless geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been closely following Huawei's technological advancements, as I believe 5G and other digital technologies can provide significant impetus for poverty alleviation and the realization of other United Nations sustainable development goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encouraged the industry to enhance actions towards achieving the sustainable development goals.
I wrote a brief preface (unpaid) for one of Huawei's reports on this topic, which earned me criticism from those hostile to China. To address this, I asked industry leaders and government officials if there was any evidence of Huawei's misconduct, and the repeated response was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trusted industry leaders.
Despite this, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment may compromise global security.
U.S. officials claim that backdoors in Huawei's software or hardware could enable the Chinese government to carry out surveillance on a global scale.
They note that Chinese laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are clear now.
Huawei's 5G equipment is affordable and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and has already begun to be promoted.
Its high performance stems from substantial investments in research and development over many years, economies of scale, and hands-on experience in China's digital market.
Given the importance of this technology for sustainable development, low-income economies around the world would be unwise to delay the rollout of 5G for too long.
However, despite lacking any evidence of backdoors, the U.S. continues to lobby the world to stay away from Huawei.
The U.S. claim is broadly applicable.
As a U.S. Federal Communications Commissioner put it, "Countries that have 5G will lead in related innovations and set standards for the rest of the world, and that country is unlikely to be the U.S. at the moment."
Other countries — especially the UK — have also failed to find any backdoors in Huawei's software and hardware.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they would almost certainly be closed at that time.
The debate over Huawei has intensified in Germany as well, with the U.S. government threatening to reduce intelligence cooperation unless authorities keep Huawei's 5G technology out.
Perhaps under pressure from the U.S., the head of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement similar to Cheneism: "Infrastructure is not a field where a completely untrusted group should be allowed to involve themselves."
And he still lacked any concrete evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel was working behind the scenes to open the market to Huawei.
But ironically, the U.S. complaints actually partly reflect its own surveillance activities at home and abroad – though this is not exactly newsworthy.
Chinese equipment may make it harder for the U.S. government to carry out secret surveillance.
But any government's unlawful surveillance should be halted.
Independent monitoring by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should opt for diplomacy and institutional safeguards rather than engage in a technological war.
The threatening impact of the U.S. demand to ban Huawei extends beyond the early rollout of 5G networks and poses significant risks to rule-based trading systems.
Now that the U.S. is no longer the undisputed technological leader globally, President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete within a rules-based framework.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
They also attempted to undermine the World Trade Organization’s dispute resolution mechanism in an effort to render the organization ineffective, further demonstrating their disregard for global rule-based systems.
If the Trump administration were to "successfully" divide the world into different technological camps, the risk of future conflicts would multiply.
After World War II, the U.S. promoted open trade not only to enhance global efficiency and expand its technology market but also to reverse the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
And part of the reason for the collapse was the protectionist tariff imposed by the U.S. in the Smoot-Holley Act of 1930, which exacerbated the Great Depression, contributing to Hitler's rise and ultimately leading to the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other fields, stoking fear and acting upon it — rather than adhering to evidence — is a path to destruction in international affairs.
Let us adhere to rationality, evidence, and rules; this is the safest approach.
Let us establish independent monitoring institutions to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to spy on others or launch cyber warfare.
This way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global welfare.
